# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1878-major-league-baseball-season
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1878-major-league-baseball-season/1874-in-baseball] The following are the baseball events of the year 1874 throughout the world.
[src:1878-major-league-baseball-season/1875-in-baseball] The following are the baseball events of the year 1875 throughout the world.
[src:1878-major-league-baseball-season/1876-major-league-baseball-season] The **1876 major league baseball season** was contested from April 22 through October 21, 1876, and saw the Chicago White Stockings as the pennant winner of the inaugural season of the National League and of Major League baseball.
[src:1878-major-league-baseball-season/1876-major-league-baseball-season] Two non-NA teams would join as charter members, including the Cincinnati Reds (unrelated to the modern team) and Louisville Grays.
[src:1878-major-league-baseball-season/1876-major-league-baseball-season] The 1876 schedule was formatted so that each team would play up to 10 games against each team in the league (split evenly between home and away games), for a maximum of 70 games (only fulfilled by the Boston Red Caps).
[src:1878-major-league-baseball-season/1876-major-league-baseball-season] Any game played against a team at home must be played within two months' time away, "under penalty of forfeiture." This was the only season that the National League adopted this format.
[src:1878-major-league-baseball-season/1876-major-league-baseball-season] The following season would see a more regulated format, requiring teams to schedule 12 games against each team.
[src:1878-major-league-baseball-season/1876-major-league-baseball-season] Opening Day took place on April 22 featuring a game between the Boston Red Caps and Athletics of Philadelphia.
[src:1878-major-league-baseball-season/1876-major-league-baseball-season] The final day of the season was on October 21, featuring a game between the Hartford Dark Blues and Boston Red Caps.
[src:1878-major-league-baseball-season/1876-major-league-baseball-season] The first doubleheader in major league history occurred on September 9 between the Cincinnati Reds and Hartford Dark Blues.
[src:1878-major-league-baseball-season/1876-major-league-baseball-season] The year ended with the first postseason competition in major league history.
[src:1878-major-league-baseball-season/1876-major-league-baseball-season] The contest featured the first and second-place regular season finishers.
[src:1878-major-league-baseball-season/1876-major-league-baseball-season] Three tie games, which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind occurred throughout the season (though standings were determined by total wins, not winning percentage).
[src:1878-major-league-baseball-season/1876-major-league-baseball-season] The Louisville Grays had three tie games.
[src:1878-major-league-baseball-season/1876-major-league-baseball-season] The Hartford Dark Blues, New York Mutuals, and Philadelphia Athletics had one tie game each.
[src:1878-major-league-baseball-season/1876-major-league-baseball-season] The Hartford Dark Blues would play their final game at the Hartford Ball Club Grounds on September 16 against the St.
[src:1878-major-league-baseball-season/1876-major-league-baseball-season] Louis Brown Stockings, relocating to Brooklyn, New York at the Union Grounds as the Brooklyn Hartfords for the start of the 1877 season.
[src:1878-major-league-baseball-season/1877-major-league-baseball-season] The **1877 major league baseball season** was contested from April 30 through October 6, 1877, and saw the Boston Red Caps as the pennant winner of the second season of the National League.
[src:1878-major-league-baseball-season/1877-major-league-baseball-season] Over the off-season, in December 1876, two teams were formally kicked out of the league for failing to fulfill their schedules: New York Mutuals and Philadelphia Athletics, contracting the league from eight to six teams.
[src:1878-major-league-baseball-season/1877-major-league-baseball-season] The Hartford Dark Blue would relocate from Hartford, Connecticut to Brooklyn, New York, as the Brooklyn Hartfords.
[src:1878-major-league-baseball-season/1877-major-league-baseball-season] The 1877 schedule consisted of 60 games for all six teams of the National League.
[src:1878-major-league-baseball-season/1877-major-league-baseball-season] Each team was scheduled to play 12 games against the other five teams in the league.
[src:1878-major-league-baseball-season/1877-major-league-baseball-season] This was the first season that the National League adopted the format.
[src:1878-major-league-baseball-season/1877-major-league-baseball-season] The format would last only through the following season.
[src:1878-major-league-baseball-season/1877-major-league-baseball-season] Opening Day took place on April 30 featuring a game between the Boston Red Caps and Brooklyn Hartfords.
[src:1878-major-league-baseball-season/1877-major-league-baseball-season] The final day of the season was on October 6, featuring four teams.
[src:1878-major-league-baseball-season/1877-major-league-baseball-season] The Brooklyn Hartfords hosted a neutral site game.
[src:1878-major-league-baseball-season/1877-major-league-baseball-season] The Brooklyn Hartfords had two tie games.
[src:1878-major-league-baseball-season/1877-major-league-baseball-season] The Boston Red Caps, Chicago White Stockings, Cincinnati Reds, and Louisville Grays had one tie game each.
[src:1878-major-league-baseball-season/1877-major-league-baseball-season] The Chicago White Stockings would play their final game at 23rd Street Grounds on October 6 against the Louisville Grays, moving to Lakefront Park for the start of the 1878 season.
[src:1878-major-league-baseball-season/1877-major-league-baseball-season] The Brooklyn Hartfords hosted a neutral site game against the Chicago White Stockings on their last home game of the season, September 22, at the site of the former National Association's New Haven Elm Citys, at the Howard Avenue Grounds in New Haven, Connecticut.
[src:1878-major-league-baseball-season/1878-boston-red-caps-season] The **1878 Boston Red Caps season** was the eighth season of the franchise.
[src:1878-major-league-baseball-season/1878-boston-red-caps-season] The Red Caps won their second straight National League pennant.
[src:1878-major-league-baseball-season/1878-chicago-white-stockings-season] The **1878 Chicago White Stockings season** was the seventh season of the Chicago White Stockings franchise, the third in the National League and the first at Lakefront Park.
[src:1878-major-league-baseball-season/1878-chicago-white-stockings-season] The White Stockings finished fourth in the National League with a record of 30–30.
[src:1878-major-league-baseball-season/1878-cincinnati-reds-season] The **1878 Cincinnati Reds season** was a season in American baseball.
[src:1878-major-league-baseball-season/1878-cincinnati-reds-season] The team finished second in the National League with a record of 37–23, four games behind the Boston Red Caps.
[src:1878-major-league-baseball-season/1878-cincinnati-reds-season] After finishing their first two seasons in the National League in last place, the Reds were hoping for some improvement in the 1878 season.
[src:1878-major-league-baseball-season/1878-cincinnati-reds-season] Cincinnati signed Cal McVey of the Chicago White Stockings to become the team's new third baseman, and new manager.
[src:1878-major-league-baseball-season/1878-cincinnati-reds-season] Catcher Deacon White of the Boston Red Caps signed with Cincinnati.
[src:1878-major-league-baseball-season/1878-cincinnati-reds-season] White led the National League with a .387 batting average, 103 hits, eleven triples, 49 RBI, and a .545 slugging percentage with the Red Caps in 1877.
[src:1878-major-league-baseball-season/1878-cincinnati-reds-season] White also led the National League with 60 RBI while playing for the White Stockings in 1876.
[src:1878-major-league-baseball-season/1878-cincinnati-reds-season] On the mound, 23-year-old Will White was signed by the Reds.
[src:1878-major-league-baseball-season/1878-cincinnati-reds-season] White appeared in three games with the Boston Red Caps in 1877, going 2–1 with a 3.00 ERA.
[src:1878-major-league-baseball-season/1878-cincinnati-reds-season] Charley Jones had another very solid season with the Reds, as he had a .310 batting average, along with a team high three home runs and 39 RBI.
[src:1878-major-league-baseball-season/1878-cincinnati-reds-season] White saw his production slip, however, he still hit .314 with 29 RBI.
[src:1878-major-league-baseball-season/1878-cincinnati-reds-season] Player-manager McVey was solid with a .306 average and two home runs along with 28 RBI.
[src:1878-major-league-baseball-season/1878-cincinnati-reds-season] White had a spectacular season, going 30–21 with a 1.79 ERA in 468 innings pitched.
[src:1878-major-league-baseball-season/1878-cincinnati-reds-season] The Reds opened the season with a six-game winning streak, and stayed hot in their first twenty games, going 15–5, and were sitting in first place in the National League.
[src:1878-major-league-baseball-season/1878-cincinnati-reds-season] Cincinnati then went on a six-game losing streak, falling to 15–11, and out of first place.
[src:1878-major-league-baseball-season/1878-cincinnati-reds-season] The Reds never reclaimed first place; however, they finished the season strong, including a nine-game winning streak late in the year, to finish in second place with a 37–23 record, five games behind the first place Boston Red Caps.
[src:1878-major-league-baseball-season/1878-major-league-baseball-season] The **1878 major league baseball season** was contested from May 1 through September 30, 1878, and saw the Boston Red Caps as the pennant winner of the third season of the National League.
[src:1878-major-league-baseball-season/1878-major-league-baseball-season] Over the off-season, in December 1877, two teams would fold: Brooklyn Hartfords and St.
[src:1878-major-league-baseball-season/1878-major-league-baseball-season] They were replaced by the Indianapolis Blues and Milwaukee Grays.
[src:1878-major-league-baseball-season/1878-major-league-baseball-season] Later in the offseason, the Providence Grays would join on February 6, raising the number of teams to seven.
[src:1878-major-league-baseball-season/1878-major-league-baseball-season] On April 1 or 2, the Louisville Grays would officially resign from the league, once again lowering the number of teams to six.
[src:1878-major-league-baseball-season/1878-major-league-baseball-season] The 1878 schedule consisted of 60 games for all six teams of the National League.
[src:1878-major-league-baseball-season/1878-major-league-baseball-season] This format had been in place since the previous season, and would be the final season which saw this format, due to expansion to eight teams the following season.
[src:1878-major-league-baseball-season/1878-major-league-baseball-season] Opening Day took place on May 1 featuring all six teams.
[src:1878-major-league-baseball-season/1878-major-league-baseball-season] The final day of the season was on September 30, featuring a game between the Boston Red Caps and Providence Grays.
[src:1878-major-league-baseball-season/1878-major-league-baseball-season] Two teams hosted games at neutral sites, the Indianapolis Blues and Providence Grays.
[src:1878-major-league-baseball-season/1878-major-league-baseball-season] Four tie games, which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind occurred throughout the season (though standings were determined by total wins, not winning percentage).
[src:1878-major-league-baseball-season/1878-major-league-baseball-season] The Indianapolis Blues had three tie games.
[src:1878-major-league-baseball-season/1878-major-league-baseball-season] The Chicago White Stockings, Cincinnati Reds, and Milwaukee Grays had one tie game each.
[src:1878-major-league-baseball-season/1878-major-league-baseball-season] Any team shown in small text indicates a previous team a player was on during the season.
[src:1878-major-league-baseball-season/1878-major-league-baseball-season] The Chicago White Stockings leave the 23rd Street Grounds (where they played for four seasons since their National Association days from 1874) and move to Lakefront Park where they would play for seven seasons through 1884.
